{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496704"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:54:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:54:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1404"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1404"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.12,0.13,0.23,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89467"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1404"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73599"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"325"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1554"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2267"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15349"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89467"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of increasing left-sided abdominal pain. He has a medical history of atrial fibrillation and epilepsy. His regular medications include warfarin and an anti-epileptic medication. Eight days ago, his General Practitioner prescribed a course of antibiotics for a chest infection. He does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 134/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft, apart from tenderness in the left lower quadrant. Investigations reveal an INR of 6.0 (2.0-3.0). A CT scan of the abdomen is arranged (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications would best explain the patient\u0027s current situation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Erythromycin","Carbamazepine","Rifampicin","Amoxicillin","Phenytoin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a large left-sided rectus sheath haematoma (Image). This patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with over-anticoagulation, which is the most common cause of rectus sheath haematoma. The elevated INR of 6.0 (therapeutic range 2.0-3.0) confirms excessive anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is the antibiotic most likely to explain this patient\u0027s current situation. It is an inhibitor of the CYP450 enzyme system, which is responsible for metabolising warfarin in the liver. By inhibiting this system, erythromycin decreases the metabolism of warfarin, causing increased serum warfarin levels and a subsequent prolongation of the INR. This interaction can lead to over-anticoagulation and increase the risk of bleeding complications, such as the rectus sheath haematoma seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarbamazepine, rifampicin \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Ephenytoin \u003C/strong\u003Eare all inducers of the CYP450 enzyme system. They would increase the metabolism of warfarin, potentially leading to reduced anticoagulation and a lower INR. This effect is opposite to what we see in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E generally does not have a significant effect on the CYP450 system or warfarin metabolism. While it can potentially alter intestinal flora and affect vitamin K synthesis, it is less likely to cause such a dramatic increase in INR compared to erythromycin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn patients who are stable with no significant drop in haemoglobin, rectus sheath haematomas can often be managed conservatively with analgesia, compression, and reversal of anticoagulation. More unstable patients may require aggressive treatment, including possible radiological embolisation to stop bleeding into the haematoma. This case highlights the importance of careful medication management in patients on warfarin, particularly when prescribing antibiotics or other medications that can interact with the CYP450 system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Antibiotics must be used with care in patients on warfarin.","Erythromycin inhibits the CYP450 system, leading to increased warfarin levels and prolonged INR.","Rectus sheath haematoma is a potential complication of over-anticoagulation."],"references":["Lynch T. The Effect of Cytochrome P450 Metabolism on Drug Response, Interactions, and Adverse Effects. AFP. 2007:76(3). Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2007/0801/p391.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73599"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1404"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15977"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20841"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15977"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ee8aa750-d7fa-49af-94eb-db137bbe7688.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ee8aa750-d7fa-49af-94eb-db137bbe7688.jpg","isProcessed":t